==Chemical Sciences : A manual for CSIR-UGC National Eligibility Test for Lectureship and JRF==
How to you this textbook:


{{BookCat}}

The Joint CSIR-UGC JRF/LS (NET) Examination shall comprise 2 papers. Latest Information is available [[http://www.csirhrdg.res.in/CSS.pdf here]]
#[[http://www.csirhrdg.res.in/CSS.pdf CHEMICAL SCIENCES Scheme of Examination]] #[[http://www.csirhrdg.res.in/Syllabi_NET.htm Syllabus Paper I (A) ]] #[[http://www.csirhrdg.res.in/CS.pdf Syllabus Paper I (B) & II ]] #You can download Model questions for Joint CSIR UGC Test for JRF and Eligibility for Lectureship (NET) [[http://www.csirhrdg.res.in/GS.pdf Paper I (A) GENERAL SCIENCE ]] [[http://www.csirhrdg.res.in/CHEM%20Model%20%20P1.pdf Paper I (B) CHEMICAL SCIENCES ]] [[http://www.csirhrdg.res.in/CHEM%20Model%20%20P2.pdf Paper II CHEMICAL SCIENCES ]]
{{BookCat}}

The Secure Hash Algorithm SHA (Secure Hash Algorithm), based on the MD4 (Message Digest) algorithm created by Ronald L. Rivest of the MIT. Consists in three SHA distinct algorithms labeled SHA-0, SHA-1, and SHA-2.

SHA-1 was considered a cryptographically secure one-way hash algorithm (some weaknesses have already been found). It was designed by the NIST (National Institute of Standards and Technology), along with the NSA (National Security Agency), see the [http://www.itl.nist.gov/fipspubs/fip180-1.htm Secure Hash Standard FIPS 180-1].

{{BookCat}}

