The '''Sommelet-Hauser rearrangement''' is a [[rearrangement reaction]] of certain [[benzyl]] [[quaternary ammonium salt]]s <ref>[[Organic Syntheses]], Coll. Vol. 4, p.585 (1963); Vol. 34, p.61 (1954) [http://orgsynth.org/orgsyn/pdfs/CV4P0585.pdf Link].</ref>. The reagent is [[sodium amide]] or another alkali metal amide and the reaction product a N-dialkyl benzyl amine with a new [[alkyl]] group in the [[aromatic ortho position]]. 

:[[File:SommeletHauserReaction.svg|Sommelet-Hauser rearrangement]]

This reaction was named after M. Sommelet <ref>M. Sommelet, Compt. Rend. 205, 56 (1937).</ref> and Charles R. Hauser <ref>''Rearrangements of Benzyltrimethylammonium Ion and Related Quaternary Ammonium Ions by Sodium Amide Involving Migration into the Ring'' Simon W. Kantor, Charles R. Hauser [[J. Am. Chem. Soc.]], '''1951''', 73 (9), pp 4122–4131 [[doi:10.1021/ja01153a022]]</ref>

==Mechanism==
The benzylic methylene proton is acidic and deprotonation takes place to the [[ylide]]. The second step is a [[2,3-sigmatropic rearrangement]].

:[[File:SommeletHauserMechanism.svg|Sommelet-Hauser mechanism]]

