The Athinoula A. Martinos Center for Biomedical Imaging, usually referred to as just the "Martinos Center," is a major hub of [[neuropsychological]] research and [[nuclear magnetic resonance]] research and development in Boston. The center has two sites, one in the [[Massachusetts General Hospital]] East Campus in the [[Charlestown Navy Yard]], and another at [[MIT]]. The center is a member or collaborator with NCRR (and [[Biomedical Informatics Research Network|BIRN]]), NIDA, NIBIB, National Cancer Institute, NINDS, NCCAM, ONDCP, and The MIND Institute. The center also has a strategic partnership with Siemens Medical Solutions. It is also a Harvard Catalyst site.
There are 8 [[MRI]] scanning bays used primarily for research, including a 7 [[Tesla (unit)|Tesla]] magnet for human radiography and a combined [[Positron emission tomography| PET]]-MRI. In addition, the center serves as a development site for new Siemens equipment, such as the 32 channel and 128 channel MRI coils.
==References== *[http://martinos.org/martinos/research/index.php Martinos Center Research] *[http://martinos.org/martinos/aboutUs/index.php Martinos Center About Overview] *[http://www.martinos.org/martinos/research/tourGeneral/tour-01.htm Martinos Center Virtual Tour] *[http://www.nmr.mgh.harvard.edu/martinos/ctrFunding/siemensAgreement.php Martinos Center Strategic Partnership with Siemens Medical Solutions] *[http://www.nmr.mgh.harvard.edu/martinos/ctrFunding/sources.php Martinos Center Major Funding Sources and Initiatives] *[http://www.siemens.com/innovation/en/publikationen/publications_pof/pof_fall_2005/research_cooperation.htm Siemens AG Research Cooperation with the Martinos Center] *[http://www.healthimaging.com/index.php?option=com_articles&view=article&id=17535 HealthImaging:Automated MRI measures may identify early Alzheimer's at] *[http://www.nytimes.com/2007/05/28/health/28stroke.html?_r=1&pagewanted=print New York Times: Lost Chances for Survival, Before and After Stroke] *[http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/11/19/AR2007111900907_pf.html The Washington Post: Migraine Tied to Thickening in Brain Area] *[http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/01/18/AR2007011800997.html The Washington Post: Scientists Probe the Idle Mind]
