[[Image:LTQ-FTICR.jpg|thumb|right|200 px|Hybrid linear ion trap Fourier transform ion cyclotron resonance mass spectrometer]] A '''hybrid mass spectrometer''' is a device for [[tandem mass spectrometry]] that consists of a combination of two or more ''[[m/z]]'' separation devices of different types.
==Notation== The different ''m/z'' separation elements of a hybrid [[mass spectrometer]] can be represented by a shorthand notation. The symbol ''Q'' represents a [[quadrupole mass analyzer]], ''q'' is a [[radio frequency]] collision quadrupole, ''TOF'' is a [[time-of-flight mass spectrometer]], ''B'' is a magnetic [[sector mass spectrometer|sector]] and ''E'' is an electric sector.
==Sector quadrupole== A [[sector instrument]] can be combined with a collision quadrupole and [[quadrupole mass analyzer]] to form a hybrid instrument. <ref name=Glish1982>{{Cite journal | last = Glish | first = G. | year = 1982 | title = A new “hybrid” sector/quadrupole mass spectrometer for mass spectrometry/mass spectrometry | journal = International Journal or Mass Spectrometry and Ion Physics | volume = 41 | pages = 157 | doi = 10.1016/0020-7381(82)85032-8 | last2 = McLuckey | first2 = S | last3 = Ridley | first3 = T | last4 = Cooks | first4 = R | postscript = <!--None-->}}</ref> A BEqQ configuration with a magnetic sector (B), electric sector (E), collision quadrupole (q) and ''m/z'' selection quadrupole (Q) have been constructed<ref name=Schoen1985>{{Cite journal | last = Schoen | first = A. | year = 1985 | title = A hybrid BEQQ mass spectrometer | journal = International Journal of Mass Spectrometry and Ion Processes | volume = 65 | pages = 125 | doi = 10.1016/0168-1176(85)85059-X | last2 = Amy | first2 = J.W. | last3 = Ciupek | first3 = J.D. | last4 = Cooks | first4 = R.G. | last5 = Dobberstein | first5 = P. | last6 = Jung | first6 = G. | postscript = <!--None-->}}</ref><ref name=Harrison1986>{{Cite journal | last = Harrison | first = A. | year = 1986 | title = A hybrid BEQQ mass spectrometer for studies in gaseous ion chemistry | journal = International Journal of Mass Spectrometry and Ion Processes | volume = 74 | pages = 13 | doi = 10.1016/0168-1176(86)85020-0 | postscript = <!--None-->}}</ref> and an instrument with two electric sectors (BEEQ) has been described.<ref name=Winger1992>{{Cite journal | last = Winger | first = B. E. | year = 1992 | title = Hybrid BEEQ tandem mass spectrometer for the study of ion/surface collision processes | journal = Review of Scientific Instruments | volume = 63 | pages = 5613 | doi = 10.1063/1.1143391 | last2 = Laue | first2 = H. -J. | last3 = Horning | first3 = S. R. | last4 = Julian | first4 = R. K. | last5 = Lammert | first5 = S. A. | last6 = Riederer | first6 = D. E. | last7 = Cooks | first7 = R. G. | postscript = <!--None-->}}</ref>
==Quadrupole time-of-flight== [[Image:Q-TOF.jpg|thumb|right|250 px|Hybrid quadrupole time-of-flight mass spectrometer.]] A [[triple quadrupole mass spectrometer]] with the final quadrupole replaced by a time-of-flight device is known is a quadrupole time-of-flight instrument.<ref name="pmid10815976">{{cite journal |author=Shevchenko A, Loboda A, Shevchenko A, Ens W, Standing KG |title=MALDI quadrupole time-of-flight mass spectrometry: a powerful tool for proteomic research |journal=Anal. Chem. |volume=72 |issue=9 |pages=2132–41 |year=2000 |month=May |pmid=10815976 |doi= 10.1021/ac9913659|url=}}</ref><ref name="pmid11473401">{{cite journal |author=Steen H, Küster B, Mann M |title=Quadrupole time-of-flight versus triple-quadrupole mass spectrometry for the determination of phosphopeptides by precursor ion scanning |journal=J Mass Spectrom |volume=36 |issue=7 |pages=782–90 |year=2001 |month=July |pmid=11473401 |doi=10.1002/jms.174}}</ref> Such an instrument can be represented as QqTOF.
==Ion trap time-of-flight== In an ion trap instrument, ions are trapped in a [[quadrupole ion trap]] and then injected into the TOF. The trap can be 3-D<ref name="pmid7517726">{{cite journal |author=Fountain ST, Lee H, Lubman DM |title=Ion fragmentation activated by matrix-assisted laser desorption/ionization in an ion-trap/reflectron time-of-flight device |journal=Rapid Commun. Mass Spectrom. |volume=8 |issue=5 |pages=407–16 |year=1994 |month=May |pmid=7517726 |doi=10.1002/rcm.1290080514 |url=}}</ref> or a linear trap.<ref name=Campbell1998>{{Cite journal | last = Campbell | first = J. M. | year = 1998 | title = A new linear ion trap time-of-flight system with tandem mass spectrometry capabilities | journal = Rapid Communications in Mass Spectrometry | volume = 12 | pages = 1463 | doi = 10.1002/(SICI)1097-0231(19981030)12:20<1463::AID-RCM357>3.0.CO;2-H | last2 = Collings | first2 = B. A. | last3 = Douglas | first3 = D. J. | postscript = <!--None-->}}</ref>
==Linear ion trap and Fourier transform mass analyzers== A linear ion trap combined with a [[Fourier transform ion cyclotron resonance]]<ref name="pmid15253445">{{cite journal |author=Syka JE, Marto JA, Bai DL, ''et al.'' |title=Novel linear quadrupole ion trap/FT mass spectrometer: performance characterization and use in the comparative analysis of histone H3 post-translational modifications |journal=J. Proteome Res. |volume=3 |issue=3 |pages=621–6 |year=2004 |pmid=15253445 |doi= 10.1021/pr0499794|url=}}</ref> or [[orbitrap]]<ref name="pmid16579588">{{cite journal |author=Makarov A, Denisov E, Kholomeev A, Balschun W, Lange O, Strupat K, Horning S |title=Performance evaluation of a hybrid linear ion trap/orbitrap mass spectrometer |journal=Anal. Chem. |volume=78 |issue=7 |pages=2113–20 |year=2006 |pmid=16579588 |doi=10.1021/ac0518811}}</ref><ref name="pmid16249172">{{cite journal |author=Olsen JV, de Godoy LM, Li G, ''et al.'' |title=Parts per million mass accuracy on an Orbitrap mass spectrometer via lock mass injection into a C-trap |journal=Mol. Cell Proteomics |volume=4 |issue=12 |pages=2010–21 |year=2005 |month=December |pmid=16249172 |doi=10.1074/mcp.T500030-MCP200 |url=http://www.mcponline.org/cgi/pmidlookup?view=long&pmid=16249172}}</ref><ref name="pmid16408932">{{cite journal |author=Yates JR, Cociorva D, Liao L, Zabrouskov V |title=Performance of a linear ion trap-Orbitrap hybrid for peptide analysis |journal=Anal. Chem. |volume=78 |issue=2 |pages=493–500 |year=2006 |month=January |pmid=16408932 |doi=10.1021/ac0514624}}</ref> mass spectrometer is marketed by [[Thermo Scientific]] as the LTQ FT and LTQ Orbitrap, respectively.
