'''Ion-attachment mass spectrometry''' ('''IAMS''') is a form of [[mass spectrometry]] that uses a "soft" form of ionization similar to [[chemical ionization]] in which a cation is attached to the analyte molecule in a reactive collision:
:<math>M + X^+ + A \to MX^+ + A</math> 

Where M is the analyte molecule, X<sup>+</sup> is the cation and A is a non-reacting collision partner.<ref> {{cite journal|title=Lithium ion attachment mass spectrometry: Instrumentation and features|journal=Review of Scientific Instruments|date=|first=|last=|coauthors=|volume=|issue=|pages=|id= |url=|format=|accessdate=2007-11-01 }}</ref>

==Principle==
This technique is applicable to gases or any materials that can be vaporized. It uses a non-fragmenting non-conventional ionisation mode, by attachment of a lithium (or alkaline) ion to the gas to be analysed with a more traditional mass filter. This instrument is more dedicated to analysis of moderately-sized molecules such as organic or aromatic compounds.<ref> {{cite journal|title=Aromatic ion attachment mass spectrometry: an ion-molecule reaction for organosulfur analysis|journal=Organic Mass Spectrometry|date=|first=|last=|coauthors=|volume=|issue=|pages=|id= |url=|format=|accessdate=2007-11-01 }}</ref>

==Applications==
Currently, it is used industrially to verify, with a high throughput, the concentrations of [[brominated flame retardant]]s (BFR) in plastics in compliance with [[European Union|European]] [[RoHS]] (Restriction of Hazardous Substances) regulation in place since 2006. The banned molecules include [[PBB]] and [[PBDE]], whose concentration should not exceed 0.1% w/w. <ref>{{cite web | title = The guide of environmental quality assurance for a supplier of JVC |date=July 2006 | publisher = [[JVC]] | url = http://www.jvc-victor.co.jp/company/environ/wr/gprocure/eqaguide_e.pdf}}</ref><ref>Pittcon 2006; Poster by Y. Shiokawa; The Rapid Analysis of Brominated Flame Retardants in Resin Used for Electrical Appliances by Ion Attachment Mass Spectrometry.</ref><ref> {{cite journal|title=State of bromine based flame retarding agent mixing and its countermeasure|journal=Sangyo to Kankyo|date=|first=|last=|coauthors=|volume=|issue=|pages=|id= |url=|format=|accessdate=2007-11-01 }}</ref>

IAMS has also been used to analyze diesel exhaust particles<ref name="pmid17273150">{{cite journal |author=Masaki H, Chen L, Korenaga T |title=Direct analysis of diesel exhaust particles by fragmentation-free mass spectrometry using ion attachment mass spectrometry |journal=Environmental sciences : an international journal of environmental physiology and toxicology |volume=13 |issue=6 |pages=347–52 |year=2006 |pmid=17273150 |doi=}}</ref>, in ceramic processing <ref name="pmid16579621">{{cite journal |author=Tsugoshi T, Nagaoka T, Nakamura M, Shiokawa Y, Watari K |title=Application of ion attachment mass spectrometry to evolved gas analysis for in situ monitoring of porous ceramic processing |journal=Anal. Chem. |volume=78 |issue=7 |pages=2366–9 |year=2006 |pmid=16579621 |doi=10.1021/ac0518248}}</ref> and in critical SiO<sub>2</sub> etching during semiconductor manufacturing.

